==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Frisian [[wunia]], Old Saxon [[wunon]] (Dutch [[wonen]]), Old High German [[wonen|wonēn]] (German [[wohnen]]), Old Norse [[una]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'wʊnian/}}

===Verb===
(ġe)'''wunian''' (class 2 weak: ''3 singular present'' '''[[wunaþ]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[wunode]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[wunodon]]''', ''past participle'' (ġe)'''[[wunod]]''')
# to [[reside]], to [[dwell]]
#:''Ðu geond holt wunast'': you shall live in the woods.  (Cædmon's ''Metrical Paraphrase'')
# to [[stay]] or [[remain]]
#:''Lucia on ðære ylcan stowe wunode ðe heo ofslagen wæs'': Lucia still lay in the same place she was struck down.  (Ælfric's ''Lives of Saints'')
# to live in, to [[inhabit]]
# to be used or accustomed to something
#:''Hafuc sceal on glofe wilde gewunian'': the wild hawk must grow used to the glove.  (''Maxims II'')

===Descendents===
*Middle English [[won]]

